User: What is "@media"?

Assistant: The @media CSS at-rule can be used to apply part of a style sheet based on the result of one or more media queries. With it, you specify a media query and a block of CSS to apply to the document if and only if the media query matches the device on which the content is being used.

Here's a detailed explanation:


## Try it
CSS Demo: @media

The interactive example cannot be shown because MathML is not supported by your browser.

## Syntax
The @media at-rule may be placed at the top level of your code or nested inside any other conditional group at-rule.

```css
/* At the top level of your code */
@media screen and (min-width: 900px) {
  article {
    padding: 1rem 3rem;
  }
}

/* Nested within another conditional at-rule */
@supports (display: flex) {
  @media screen and (min-width: 900px) {
    article {
      display: flex;
    }
  }
}
```

## Description
A media query's <media-query-list> includes <media-type>s, <media-feature>s, and logical operators.

## Media types
A <media-type> describes the general category of a device. Except when using the only logical operator, the media type is optional and the all type is implied.

- all: Suitable for all devices.
- print: Intended for paged material and documents viewed on a screen in print preview mode.
- screen: Intended primarily for screens.

## Media features
A <media feature> describes specific characteristics of the user agent, output device, or environment. Media feature expressions test for their presence, value, or range of values, and are entirely optional. Each media feature expression must be surrounded by parentheses.

## Logical operators
The logical operators not, and, only, and or can be used to compose a complex media query. You can also combine multiple media queries into a single rule by separating them with commas.

## User agent client hints
Some media queries have corresponding user agent client hints. These are HTTP headers that request content that is pre-optimized for the particular media requirement.

## Formal syntax
```css
@media =
  @media <media-query-list> { <rule-list> }
```

## Accessibility
To best accommodate people who adjust a site's text size, use ems when you need a <length> for your media queries. Both em and px are valid units, but em works better if the user changes the browser text size.

## Security
Because media queries provide insights into the capabilities—and by extension, the features and design—of the device the user is working with, there is the potential that they could be abused to construct a fingerprint which identifies the device.

## Examples
### Testing for print and screen media types
```css
@media print {
  body {
    font-size: 10pt;
  }
}

@media screen {
  body {
    font-size: 13px;
  }
}

@media screen, print {
  body {
    line-height: 1.2;
  }
}

@media only screen and (min-width: 320px) and (max-width: 480px) and (resolution: 150dpi) {
  body {
    line-height: 1.4;
  }
}
```

